  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony offense in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves concealing, disguising, or converting illegally obtained funds to make them appear legitimate. It is a serious crime that is often associated with organized crime, drug trafficking, fraud, and other illicit activities.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, such as the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)**, as well as under state laws. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Significant fines** (up to hundreds of thousands or millions of dollars).\n- **Prison sentences** (often ranging from several years to decades, depending on the severity of the offense).\n- **Forfeiture of assets** (seizure of property or funds connected to the crime).\n\nMoney laundering charges can be brought against individuals, businesses, or organizations involved in the process, including those who knowingly facilitate the activity. If you are facing such allegations, it is crucial to seek legal counsel immediately.",
